1. # **Chapter One: Introduction**

   1. ## **Background to the Study**

Valvular Heart Disease (VHD) is a condition where one, some, or all the valves of the heart are infected, which includes the mitral, tricuspid, aortic, and pulmonary valves. This then affects the normal flow of blood and causes the heart to function abnormally [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023; Al-Issa & Alqudah, 2022; Davidsen et al., 2023; Z. Jiang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?fhPt7n). This infection can then cause stenosis, which is a primary form of valve malfunction in VHD, where the heart valve gets narrow and prevents blood discharge, or regurgitation, another primary form of valve malfunction in VHD, where the heart valve does not close properly, causing leakage  [(Al-Issa & Alqudah, 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?t5DQIw). Common types of VHD include aortic stenosis (AS), aortic regurgitation (AR), mitral regurgitation (MR), mitral stenosis (MS), tricuspid regurgitation (TR), and mitral valve prolapse (MVP). VHD affects the aging population more, mainly because of the breakdown of their tissue and organ function. Still, it can also affect people because of rheumatic fever (rheumatic heart disease \[RHD\]), congenital malformations, ischemic necrosis, infection, or trauma [(Santangelo et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?LwX388). Other factors that contribute to VHD include hypertension, diabetes, and chronic kidney disease. VHD is a leading cause of morbidity and mortality globally, thereby causing panic in healthcare systems. The global incidence of VHD has increased by 45% in the last 30 years [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?iNmw0d), with a prevalence estimated at 5–10% in patients between the ages of 65–74 and 10–20% in patients over 75 years of age [(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?dYDgR0). It has been projected that VHD in Western countries could double by 2050, and that would lead to more deaths, hospital admissions, and healthcare expenses [(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?wW1ujp). Detecting VHD and acting on it early is key to improving patient outcomes and reducing the overall economic burden, because if severe VHD is left untreated, it can be very dangerous.

Valvular heart disease (VHD) symptoms are often of the following: fatigue, breathlessness/shortness of breath, chest pain or discomfort, palpitations (irregular heartbeats), weakness, dizziness, fainting, and swelling in the ankles or feet [(Khan et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?7Dkfdd). Even with these potential signs, VHD progresses slowly most times and remains asymptomatic in its early stages, which leads to medical practitioners not being able to diagnose and detect the disease early [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?GfgEGl). The public not being very aware of VHD, as they are for other conditions like cancer or heart attack, and clinicians' inadequate skill in cardiac auscultation using stethoscopes, which is the simplest and primary cost-effective screening tool, worsens the delay [(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?WKW2Yi). Unfortunately, once the damage to the valve is done, no medical therapy can prevent or reverse the progression; therefore, interventions like surgical aortic valve replacement (SAVR) or transcatheter aortic valve replacement (TAVR) remain the only curative therapeutic options [(Santangelo et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?UjS1Uz).

Cardiac auscultation is the traditional way of detecting VHD using stethoscopes, which is widely recognized as the simplest, most cost-effective, and accessible first-line screening tool. However, cardiac auscultation's accuracy is highly dependent on whether or not the clinician can detect and interpret murmurs. Studies report low sensitivity (e.g., 46% for moderate or greater VHD), even by experienced physicians, leading to underdiagnosis [(Z. Jiang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?v3KIck). Electrocardiography (ECG) is another inexpensive and non-invasive test [(Al-Mahdi et al.,](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?cb3A5f) 2025\) that is used to evaluate the heart's electrical activity and rhythms. ECG can diagnose specific VHDs like aortic stenosis (AS), aortic regurgitation (AR), and mitral regurgitation (MR), but it does not directly detect mechanical valve irregularities, which PCG is very good at [(Hangaragi et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?q36hEz). For abnormalities relating to structure and detailed functional assessment, imaging techniques like echocardiography (Echo), cardiac magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), and computed tomography (CT) are usually employed.

Phonocardiography (PCG), which visually displays heart sounds, is a useful diagnostic aid for a number of heart conditions, especially those regarding valvular heart disease (VHD) [(Al-Issa & Alqudah, 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?qnOP8n). Diagnosis of cardiovascular disease can be effectively done with PCG analysis, using a non-invasive, inexpensive, and quick methodology [(Li et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?xovQ7V). Its low cost and ease of access makes the method feasible to engage in expansive practice, especially at primary health care sites, remote health monitoring, or medically underserved communities lacking echocardiography or other more expensive imaging modalities [(Davidsen et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?WjK824). PCG technology can be incorporated into mobile health and digital stethoscope technology which allows for ease of use, large-scale screening, and remote patient monitoring for the purposes of “reaching the masses” and effectively detecting heart valve problems early on, which can inform intervention and potentially improve patient outcomes [(Santangelo et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?kVixTG). 

One of the greatest obstacles in applying PCG to automated analysis is the vulnerability of heart sound recordings to various noise and artefacts [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?P2WVd4). Regarding PCG signal corruption, external noise can be high- and low-frequency environmental noise, human speech, and friction between the stethoscope and skin. Internal noises, such as respiratory sounds and bowel sounds, can also interfere with PCG recordings. These noises can hide or imitate important features of heart sounds. This leads to difficult, if not near impossible, identification of what is S1, S2, or pathological murmurs or clicks [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?j2nLw7). Noise affects the electronic stethoscope not just in relation to data quality, but also the accuracy of analysis of gas signals. This can impact inappropriate diagnosis if not combated with advanced pre-processing and algorithms for data denoising [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?AEZNdQ).

The need for faster, cheaper, and more consistent diagnostic methods when confronted with escalating cardiovascular disease prevalence has motivated the rise of Artificial Intelligence (AI) in cardiac diagnosis [(Jaltotage et al., 2024; L. Jiang et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?OWZqn2). AI, with its speed, accuracy, and ability to analyze large amounts of complex, diverse data, offers a viable solution to enhance early detection, reduce diagnostic errors, and provide personalized treatment plans.  
Deep learning models are now widely used across various data modalities, including phonocardiogram (PCG) signals, electrocardiograms (ECGs), and various cardiac imaging data like echocardiography, computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) [(Alasmari et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?6PWs6w). AI models have had quite the success in classifying murmurs and detecting valve damage. For instance, AI-enabled digital stethoscopes have shown superior sensitivity (e.g., 94.1%) compared to physicians (41.2%) in detecting moderate or severe valvular heart disease (VHD) from heart sounds, with diagnostic accuracies up to 99.9% for detection from raw PCG signals and 98.5% for classifying five different heart valvular conditions [(Bamford et al., 2024; Z. Jiang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?4GGkKw). Deep learning models like ValveNet have demonstrated high accuracy (AU-ROC 0.77-0.88) in detecting moderate or severe aortic stenosis (AS), aortic regurgitation (AR), and mitral regurgitation (MR) from standard 12-lead ECGs, identifying patterns that the human eye often cannot perceive [(Wu & Guo, 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Vw2Y9P). Furthermore, AI has made echocardiogram interpretation for VHD diagnosis in cardiac imaging, 3D reconstruction of cardiac structures from CT/Echo, and advanced analysis of myocardial function and tissue characteristics from MRI. This reduces manual measurement time by over 50% and improves consistency and precision [(Khan et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ENkliR). These advancements have drawn special attention to AI's potential in transforming cardiac diagnostics, making it more efficient, scalable, and accurate for patient care.

Although Artificial Intelligence (AI) models for valvular heart disease (VHD) have promising diagnostic benefits, they still face several limitations, mostly due to their single-modal nature and inbuilt challenges. Phonocardiogram (PCG) models are promising for initial screening because they are cost-effective. Still, they struggle with noise interference, inter-patient variability, and the scarcity of high-quality, standardized datasets. These limitations can affect their generalizability and their clinical use, which extends beyond simply distinguishing normal from abnormal heart sounds [(Oliveira et al., 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?fMnFYK). Electrocardiogram (ECG)-based models have shown potential in detecting conditions like aortic stenosis (AS), aortic regurgitation (AR), and mitral regurgitation (MR) by identifying subtle patterns. Still, they are prone to reporting high rates of false positives, may miss structural anomalies that are not reflected in the heart’s electrical activity. They can sometimes show decreased accuracy in older patients or those with complex QRS complexes [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?eWJ1kT). A big problem most AI approaches face is the "black box" problem, where the complicated decision-making processes of deep learning algorithms are opaque, making it hard for clinicians to trust, explain, and widely adopt in clinical practice [(Al-Mahdi et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ERHnxp). Furthermore, AI models are also susceptible to bias introduced by imbalanced or unrepresentative training datasets, which can lead to reduced generalisability across diverse patient demographics and different healthcare systems [(Zhang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?qgI6zn). Lastly, the computational complexity of deep learning, specifically for multimodal systems, demands a considerable amount of resources, which can limit their scalability and real-time deployment in routine clinical care [(Khan et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?BBtejZ). The overreliance on single datasets further means that models often underperform during external validation, emphasizing the need for prospective, multisite studies to confirm their real-world effectiveness [(Abdessater et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?wmjGc6).

The proposed research presents a PCG-based diagnostic framework aimed at predicting valvular heart disease. The framework uses PCGs, a cheap and portable alternative to echocardiography, rather than the traditional various clinical modalities. It utilizes deep learning models, specifically convolutional neural networks (CNN), which can be trained with PCG spectrograms. The CNN can learn temporal and spectral patterns to capture the time-varying bioacoustic heart sounds. I extract fractal and entropy-based features using different methods to capture the non-linear, compounded-based complexity exhibited by the heart signals. Both deep feature representations and fractal features are then put into an ensemble classifier (XGBoost) to improve predictive performance, robustness to noise and reliability, and use explainable AI for model assessments and interpretability.

2. ## **Statement of the Problem**

Valvular Heart Disease (VHD) still stands as a significant cause of global cardiovascular morbidity and mortality [(Santangelo et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?5Ewkb3). While echocardiography is the gold standard for diagnosis, the expense, equipment requirements, and need for specialist interpretation limits its scalability in low- and middle-income-level environments [(Poterucha et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?DomqCi). Phonocardiography (PCG), which accesses heart sounds via digital stethoscopes, presents a less expensive, more portable alternative [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?GalaJH). The barriers to overcome with PCG analysis, however, are formidable: heart sounds are frequently tainted by noise; sounds have inconsistent duration/quality; and conventional machine learning approaches depend on handcrafted features, inferred characteristics of heart sounds, that do not transfer across groups [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?rrqJk7).

Recent deep learning methods with application to PCG spectrograms have shown high classification accuracy with VHD, but suffer from overfitting; lack interpretability; and often fail to include potentially meaningful non-linear dynamics of the signals [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?I5nAG1). The lack of robust fusion approaches between deep-features and handcrafted features (e.g., fractal and entropy features) yield non-optimal diagnostic classification performance [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?e4hUuc). This suggests the need for a complete PCG-based prediction framework based on the integration of both deep features and fractal features, with appropriate optimization strategies [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?IQ2790), and interpretability/explainability which are important for building clinical confidence and uptake [(Ganie et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ofsbHA).

3. ## **Aim and Objectives of the Project Work**

This research aims to develop a novel explainable machine learning framework for predicting valvular heart disease, using phonocardiogram (PCG) signals.  
The objectives include:

1. To preprocess and extract relevant deep and fractal features from PCG.  
2. To propose an explainable model for predicting valvular heart disease.  
3. To evaluate the performance of the proposed explainable model using standard metrics (accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, F1-score, AUC) 

   4. ## **Significance of Project Work**

This research holds significant importance for several reasons:

* Clinical Significance: Delivers a diagnostic tool based on heart sounds that is scalable and low-cost for implementation, more broadly in primary care and low-resource settings.  
* Methodological Significance: Introduces a hybrid pipeline that utilizes deep learning and fractal feature engineering, both of which are supported by ensemble learning and fusion.  
* Scientific Contribution: Illustrates the advantages of spectral versus non-linear fractal features for heart sounds classification.  
* Practical Importance: Generates explainable outputs that may enhance clinician trust and utilization in telehealth and mobile health programs.  
* Foundation for Future Work: The methodological framework developed in this research could be extended to other cardiovascular conditions and potentially adapted for telemedicine applications, enabling remote screening and monitoring of patients with suspected heart valve disease.

  5. ## **Scope of the Project Work**

This study will solely focus on valvular heart disease identification (aortic stenosis, aortic regurgitation, mitral stenosis and mitral regurgitation) based onphonocardiogram signals. All conducted experiments will revolve around the CirCor DigiScope dataset and a hybrid pipeline of deep and fractal feature extraction, PCA-based dimensionality reduction and ensemble classifiers.

6. ## **Limitations of the Project Work**

* Using one public dataset may reduce the generalizability across different cohorts.  
* Model robustness may also be compromised due to the unknown noise contamination and dataset imbalances despite augmentation.  
* Real-time implementation and clinical validation are out of scope for now.  
* The interpretability of findings are limited by current maturity of explainable AI approaches.

  7. ## **Definition of Terms**

1. **Valvular Heart Disease (VHD)**

A type of cardiovascular disease that occurs when one or more heart valves do not open or close normally causing stenosis (narrowing) or regurgitation (leaking). The most common types are aortic stenosis, aortic regurgitation, mitral stenosis, and mitral regurgitation.

2. **Phonocardiogram (PCG)**

A digital record of heart sounds created using an electronic stethoscope. PCG captures sound data that correlates to the opening and closing of heart valves and abnormal flow (i.e. murmurs). PCG is used as the only input modality for the assigned disease prediction task in the study.

3. **Spectrogram**

A visual representation of audio data displayed over a time–frequency continuum showing how the spectral content changes in time. In this study, the PCG recordings are transformed into spectrograms for the convolutional neural network inputs.

4. **Convolutional neural network (CNN)**

A type of deep learning architecture that is particularly able to find hierarchical data patterns in images or sound spectrograms. The currently trained CNNs are used to analyze features of the PCG spectrograms to learn features related to valvular heart disease for classification.

5. **Fractal and Entropy Features**

Non-linear descriptive methods to quantify how complex and irregular the physiological signals are. Some candidate descriptors include:

* Higuchi Fractal Dimension (HFD): Quantifies signal complexity at multiple scales.  
* Katz Fractal Dimension (KFD): Measures the geometric complexity of the time-series.  
* Petrosian Fractal Dimension (PFD): Provides reliable, computation-efficient complexity for the signal.  
* Detrended Fluctuation Analysis (DFA): Measures long-term correlations in time-series.  
* Hurst Exponent: Computes persistence or randomness level of the signal.  
* Sample Entropy: Quantifies the unpredictability of time-series.  
* Approximate Entropy: Measures the information signal of time-series data.

6. **Data augmentation (PCG)**

The process of artificially augmenting the dataset by applying controlled transformations to the raw PCG signals. In the study, time stretching, pitch shifting; additive noise, and amplitude scaling are included. Data augmentation allows for improvement of model robustness and class imbalance.

7. **Principal Component Analysis (PCA)**

A dimensionality reduction method that transforms high-dimensional feature vectors into lower dimensions but preserves as much variance as possible. PCA is used in this study to help in reducing the dimensionality for fused deep and fractal features for classification.

8. **Random Forest (RF)**

An ensemble machine learning method that utilizes several decision trees to predict the last class determined by combining them together to improve classification and reduce overfitting. 

9. **Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost)**

An upgraded ensemble learning method based from gradient boosting, which is predictive learning to improve weak learners containing lots of errors. 

10. **Explainable Artificial Intelligence (XAI)**

An area of AI that interprets the internal mechanics of complex models. XAI methods including SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) are employed in the study to explore the most important features derived from the PCG data increasing transparency for end user and clinician confidence.

11. **Accuracy**

A performance metric that indicates the proportion of true results (both true positives and true negatives) among the total number of cases examined.

12. **Precision**

The ratio of true abnormal predictions, out of the total number of abnormal predictions made by the model.

13. **Recall (Sensitivity)**

The retrieval ability of the model to predict all the abnormal predictions, true positives.

14. **Specificity**

The ability of the model to identify the normal patients, true negatives, out of all normal patients.

15. **F1-Score**

The balance score between precision and recall. Often considered mathematically the model evaluation upon false positive, false negatives.

16. **Public Dataset**

Data that has been shared publicly as an aggregate of datasets, used to train and/or test machine learning methods.

17. **Diagnostic System**

A computer-based multimodal machine learning or AI system to help medical personnel with identifying and diagnosing aortic valve heart disease.

18. **Clinical Validation**

The extent to which it can be determined that the AI system ultimately developed is correct and reliable in reporting data from actual patient populations.

2. # **Chapter Two: Literature Review**

This chapter is a review of previous research on valvular heart disease (VHD) diagnosis and the application of artificial intelligence, specifically machine learning and deep learning models, towards early diagnosis. The purpose of this review is to give background information on the methods used in the research study while also mentioning the work others have done in cardiovascular disease prediction and diagnosis.

 A brief summary of valvular heart disease is presented in the beginning, including type, signs and symptoms, clinical significance. The diagnostic process is also summarized including auscultation, echocardiography, electrocardiography and cardiac magnetic resonance imaging methods, as well the challenges to current (traditional) practice, which include subjectivity within the diagnostic process, late diagnosis, and inconsistency within the diagnostic process.

 Next, the applicability of machine learning is discussed with relevance to the medical field, emphasizing the ability to identify patterns across multimodal datasets and to predict models for clinical decision support. The scope of this review is on phonocardiogram (PCG)–based detection, including signal basic fundamentals, preprocessing, feature learning (deep \+ fractal), classifiers (RF/XGBoost) and explainability to enhance predictive capabilities based on clinically relevant diagnostic information used as complementary information. 

Finally, comparison is made regarding the challenges of applying deep learning in a clinical setting, including the need for large diverse data sets, the issue of class imbalance, the presence of potential bias in datasets, and finally the issue of explainability in complex models.

1. ## **Overview of the Heart Valves**

   1. ## **Anatomy and Functional Structure of the Heart Valves**

## The heart contains four valves that function as gates so that blood can flow in a one-way system through its chambers. The tricuspid and mitral valves are positioned between the atria and ventricles, while the pulmonary and aortic valves are positioned at the end of the ventricles into the arteries. Each of the valves consists of thin tissue flaps called cusps or leaflets, with the mitral valve having two cusps and the others, three cusps.

## Structurally, layers of the connective tissue, which consists of a tough fibrosa that exists to provide strength, a flexible spongiosa that helps to cushion movement and an elastic layer that aids opening and closing all support the leaflets. All the layers are covered by smooth endothelium. The tricuspid and mitral valves are also reinforced by fibrous cords known as the chordae tendineae, secured to the papillary muscles in the ventricles to prevent backflow during contraction.

## Functionally, the valves open and close when there’s a pressure change in the cardiac cycle. When the muscles are relaxed, the atrioventricular valves open to allow blood into the ventricles while the semilunar valves remain closed. When the muscles are contracted, the atrioventricular valves shut to prevent regurgitation, and the semilunar valves open to allow blood into the pulmonary artery and aorta (National Heart, Lung, and Blood Institute, 2022).

![][image1]  
*Figure 2.1 Anatomical Location of the Heart Valves in Diastole*

When valve interstitial cells (which normally maintain the extracellular matrix) undergo pathological transformation, they may start to deposit excess collagen or calcium, and that compromises the flexibility of the valve leaflets. 

As calcification and fibrosis progress, the cusps stiffen, the orifice narrows, and then flow of blood becomes obstructed. This is seen, for example, in calcific aortic stenosis. 

If this is not checked, especially early enough, the pressure gradients that increase across the stiffened valve impose extra workload on the ventricle, and that leads to hypertrophy, chamber dilation, and eventually symptoms of heart failure [(Small et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?1Jr9Xz).

2. **Categories of Valvular Heart Disease**

Valvular heart disease (VHD) can be categorized in several ways, and that includes the structural and functional characteristics, the specific valve that has been affected, the type of dysfunction (either stenosis or regurgitation), and its underlying cause or aetiology [(Talukdar & Singh, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?jTcFTR).

1. #### **Categories by Affected Valves and Types of Dysfunction**

#### Valvular heart disease involves damage to one or more of the heart’s four valves, which are the aortic, mitral, tricuspid, and pulmonary valves [***(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)***](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?REMNUv). The dysfunction would typically fall into one or two main categories, which are stenosis or regurgitation.

Stenosis is the narrowing of the heart valves, which causes the restriction of normal blood flow, while regurgitation occurs when a valve does not close properly, therefore allowing blood to leak backwards. [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Fqc74c)  
Types of VHD based on the affected valve and nature of the problem:

* Aortic Stenosis (AS): A narrowing of the aortic valve. It is the most common type of VHD, often due to degeneration [(Sengupta et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Lnuxoj).  
* Aortic Regurgitation (AR): This occurs from the inefficient closure of the aortic valves, causing blood to flow back into the left ventricle [(Oliveira et al., 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?tF9oGI).  
* Mitral Stenosis (MS): A narrowing of the mitral heart valve, often caused by rheumatic heart disease [(Oliveira et al., 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0jypQ1).  
* Mitral Regurgitation (MR): The backward leakage of blood into the left atrium due to the improper closure of the mitral valve [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?VwEkxW).  
* Mitral Valve Prolapse (MVP): This is a condition where the mitral valve leaflets bulge back into the left atrium during contraction, which can therefore lead to mitral regurgitation   
* Tricuspid Regurgitation (TR): The backward leakage of blood into the right atrium due to the improper closure of the tricuspid valve [(Khan et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?znQdlQ).  
* Pulmonary Stenosis (PS): An acquired narrowing of the pulmonary valve, which obstructs the flow of blood from the right ventricle to the pulmonary artery and then to the lungs [(Oliveira et al., 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?y1zUlm).  
  ![][image2]  
  2. **Categories by Aetiology (Causes)**

The underlying causes of VHD influence the epidemiology and management of the disease, so classification based on causes is important [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?LhZVkg). 

* Degenerative Disease: This is the most common cause of VHD in high-income countries [(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?tdE83O). It includes calcific aortic valve disease, which is an active inflammatory process that leads to fibroids and the calcification of the valve leaflets, and degenerative mitral valve disease, which can be due to conditions like fibroelastic diseases or Barlow’s disease [(Sengupta et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?q5F8o8)  
* Rheumatic Heart Disease: This is the most common cause of VHD in low and middle-income countries [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?SXgI0F). It is known to frequently cause mitral stenosis. 

Other causes could include congenital malformations, which are abnormalities present at birth [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?29ch39), ischemic disease, which results from reduced blood flow to the heart’s muscles [(Santangelo et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?sCS1rq), and infective endocarditis, which is the infection of the heart valves that can cause damage leading to regurgitation [(Oliveira et al., 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?hogj8r).

3. **Categories for Clinical Management and Research**

VHD can also be classified based on how severe it is, either mild, moderate, or severe, and whether or not a patient is symptomatic or asymptomatic, which are very important factors necessary to determine the timing of interventions [(Khan et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?QHXcFL).   
Artificial intelligence is also being used to create new, data-driven classifications called phenogroups or phenotypes [(Sengupta et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?4aLong). These AI models analyze complex datasets like imaging, clinical data, and ECGs in order to identify different subgroups of patients that have close to the same characteristics and outcomes, which may not have been well understood through traditional classification systems [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?x4u2Aj).  
This approach helps to refine the classification of patients and could further lead to the development of more personalized treatments [(Sengupta et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?6OulSN).

3. **Importance of Symptom Recognition in Early Detection** 

Detecting the Valvular Heart Disease symptoms is important to improve the chances of survival; however, VHD remains asymptomatic in patients for years at the early stages, making symptom recognition a limited tool for early detection and diagnosis [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?rnFVsD). This long asymptomatic period presents a significant opportunity for early detection before the disease progresses to a late, more severe, and less treatable stage [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?m5bvNS).  
Patients don't usually test for VHD until they start seeing some symptoms; however, the disease might have been worse by then [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ZwTrq8). For example, aortic stenosis (AS) is known to cause death with a rate of 40-50% within a year if patients are untreated once they get symptomatic [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?rJ0f2x). This highlights a serious challenge: if Irely solely on detecting the symptoms, Irisk late diagnosis and worse patient outcomes [(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?8hVfQW). This reality calls for proactive screening and strategies for early detection that do not depend only on the patient's awareness of symptoms.  
Symptoms of valvular heart disease that are common in patients are tiredness, irregular heartbeats, and shortness of breath, mostly during physical exertion or when lying down flat [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025; Khan et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?D6x1wY). Other symptoms also include weakness, dizziness, lightheadedness, or fainting, along with chest pain or discomfort. Other conditions like swelling in the ankles, legs, or feet and fluid retention can also be indicators of VHD [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025; Khan et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?2YqTTb). Severe symptoms, especially with mitral regurgitation, may extend to persistent cough, pink frothy sputum, and visible signs of fluid accumulation like jugular distension or an enlarged liver. Migraines or headaches and anxiety or panic attacks, which are often triggered by palpitations, are also symptoms to look out for [(Khan et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?jytnA2).  
![][image3]  
Figure 2.2 *Flowchart depicting decision-making in mitral stenosis guided by symptom recognition and severity.*  
Awareness of these symptoms, as well as proactiveness when these symptoms are noticed, is the first step to VHD diagnosis, which would then lead to physical examinations and other tests like echocardiography. This initiative would enhance the decision-making process, as well as reduce the mortality rate caused by VHD.

4. ## **Diagnostic Approaches for Valvular Heart Disease**

   1. ### **Traditional Diagnostic Techniques** 

### Despite the advancement in technology and introduction of AI methods, traditional diagnostic methods for valvular heart disease (VHD), which include cardiac auscultation and echocardiography,  still remain a core method, and are often paired with newer approaches. 

1. #### **Cardiac Auscultation**

#### The most inexpensive, accessible, and always available first-line screening tool for VHD is cardiac auscultation, which involves listening to heart sounds with a stethoscope, providing initial insights into heart function and potential murmurs [***(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)***](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?FFES3E). However, its effectiveness is determined by the clinicians' ability to detect and interpret murmurs, as experienced physicians sometimes achieve sensitivities as low as 43% and specificities of 69% for diagnosing significant VHD [***(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)***](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?pMAFhC). Moreover, the emergence of newer imaging techniques has led to the decline of auscultation in clinical application [***(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)***](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?krvl7x).

![][image4]  
*Figure 2.3 Diagram showing how to auscultate for heart sounds*

2. #### **Echocardiography**

Echocardiography offers detailed insights into cardiac structure, function, and blood flow [(Canning et al., 2023; Z. Jiang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?RgVS0t). It is a highly accurate and versatile method. Although it is more resource-intensive, involves higher costs, longer examination times, and a strong dependency on the expertise of the sonographer for technically difficult images and manual measurements, making it less suitable for routine, large-scale population screening [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?BzJuyN).  
![][image5]  
*Figure 2.4 Diagram showing normal vs abnormal echocardiogram*

### **2.1.4.2  Emerging Technologies and Machine Learning Integration in VHD Detection**

New technologies, especially artificial intelligence (AI) and its subsets machine learning (ML) and deep learning (DL), are driving impressive progress in detecting valvular heart disease (VHD) [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?hOSA8E). For example, AI-supported products are being developed to broaden the framework for screening in a low-cost and scalable way, using more traditional devices such as digital stethoscopes and electrocardiograms (ECGs) [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Jv5XqD). AI algorithms can process echocardiograms using phonocardiograms (PCGs) which are visuals of heart sounds to automatically detect normal heart sound versus abnormal pathologic murmurs indicating VHD. Deep learning models, including Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), can classify unprocessed heart sounds to detect patients requiring intervention with high accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Hh8HNl). Likewise, AI can be applied to ECGs, discerning patterns invisible to the naked-eye that can indicate potential underlying VHD (aortic stenosis (AS) or mitral regurgitation (MR)) with high negative-predictive value. Utilizing such technology could focus limited resources to direct patients to expensive imaging such as echocardiograms, which are the gold standard of VHD diagnosis and assessment of severity.

The application of ML frameworks ranges from a simple screening tool to more complex diagnostic and prognostic applications. AI is enhancing the analytics of cardiac imaging from echocardiography, computed tomography (CT), and cardiac magnetic resonance (CMR) by automating view classification, quality review, and measuring structures in the image data. The automation process improves the variability of diagnostic and reduces errors introduced by human variables [(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?tpSgpI). Moreover, unsupervised machine learning is being utilized to allow for precision phenotyping, where algorithms stridulate complex datasets to unveil more individualized subpopulations of patients with different profiles and outcomes in VHD; thereby moving towards more than just a superficial classification system by severity. Ultimately, patient planning can be simulated from the analysis of CT scans for the procedural transcatheter aortic valve replacement (TAVR) machine learning frameworks were developed to perform the CT analytic processes [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?eOkuwv). These models have automated measurements, assisted in deciding which valve prosthesis to use, and simulated outcomes of the procedure in order to determine patient risk of complications. Some frameworks are exploring multi-modal approaches that implement data of ECGs, PCGs, and clinical notes into one model to operate in a more complete and accurate fashion.

## **2.2   The Role of Machine Learning and Deep Learning in Cardiology**

### **2.2.1 Overview of Machine Learning and why it matters in Cardiology**

Machine learning (ML) algorithms are a major subset of artificial intelligence (AI) and are becoming common in healthcare for analyzing complex data from different sources [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?VtD9PP). ML algorithms create mathematical models that are built from sample data to generate predictions or decisions, not limited to predicting or making decisions without being explicitly programmed for the task [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?6ih462). ML algorithms can be classified into two major categories, supervised learning where labeled data are used for classification or regression, and unsupervised learning where ML is applied to the unlabelled data to find patterns or features [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?iYbqWk). Examples of ML algorithms can be found in logistical regression, ensemble algorithms (Random Forest, Boosting), and Support Vector Machines (SVM). ML algorithms have been used across the domain of cardiology to assist with screening (classifying patients as healthy or diseased), diagnosis, risk prediction, and treatment, including the development of risk prediction algorithms for patients who underwent coronary artery disease [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?OJa9PW).   
Some common machine learning algorithms in healthcare: 

### **2.2.1.1  Support Vector Machine (SVM)**

SVM refers to a supervised learning-based AI algorithm used in classification and regression tasks. In classification, it finds the best hyperplane (i.e., a decision boundary) of the data point that can separate the data into different classes in a relatively complex high-dimensional space. SVM methods are also a problem of linear or nonlinear datum, and a machine learning-based algorithms can often be applied numerous different ways, and fit it into high-dimensional dataset, and examine tissues to formulate complicated datasets in medicine over the patients or datasets.  
![][image6]  
*Figure 2.5 Visual Representation of SVM Decision Boundary*  
 SVM has been used to classify heart sounds for diagnosing valvular hearing disease, classify heart disease based on clinical features of heart disease, applications based on clinical patient heart sound that will then analysis features from either ECG or PCG signals. One study mentioned set the highest reported SVM at an estimated 98.30 % accuracy in heart sound for classifying heart sounds  [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?mtUuR2).

### **2.2.1.2 Random Forest**

This is a powerful ensemble learning algorithm and works by building a lot of trees when building an ensemble. Each tree is built when training gets samples of random subsets of data and random subsets of features for constructing each tree, and outcomes set by the majority vote of studying all of the trees. This randomization of data and samples of random subsets of data or attributes contributes to Random Forest models robustness, reduced overfitting, or use of models that included high dimensional and complex data models [(Ganie et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Ikpukn), the most common being the studies of utilizing Random Forest algorithm used in cardiology to predict heart disease screening in heart disease, clinical demeaner etc., build risk prediction models for post-procedural outcomes, and selection of features. For example, one study using Heart Disease data concluded in predicting mortality from sequest areas under aortic stenosis using Replacement [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?wKZCtw).   
![][image7]  
*Figure 2.6 Schematics of a Random Forest with M number of Decision Trees*

### 

### **2.2.1.3  Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost)**

Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) is a machine learning algorithm used in several studies for the prediction of cardiovascular and valvular heart diseases. One model called rECHOmmend based its work on XGBoost and a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) to retain forms of valvular heart disease (VHD) and structural changes including decreased ejection fraction and ventricular septum thickness, by taking ECGs and demographics, lab results, and vitals into account [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?D1A652). Another study built an AI-enabled system based on XGBoost (among other algorithms) for the diagnosis of aortic stenosis (AS) [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?U9TYND). Similarly, a model based on XGBoost and a self-attention mechanism was also evaluated to improve predicting heart diseases [(Rahman et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?QtaIrw). In comparing an array of models, an AI model based on XGBoost presented a very high predictive accuracy of 0.95 to identify aortic stenosis [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?38CTdN), and in one study, where XGBoost was used, demonstrated excellent compatibility for classifying heart disease [(Ogunpola et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?4ZFKGs). One study noted XGBoost as the highest performing modeling for heart disease prediction using a select set of features for an accuracy of 97.57% [(Khan et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?MIhznX).

### 

### **2.2.1.4  Logistic Regression**

Logistic regression is probably the oldest and widely utilized statistical and machine learning based algorithm, which is used to organize datasets to solve binary-related classification tasks. It essentially does this by fitting the logistic (or sigmoid) function to the dataset variables, to find the highest likelihood, for binary dataset to determine a binary occurrence (a presence or absence of happening). Logistic regression uses a linear model, that may be sensible or easy to interpret, as it is extremely simple and less inductive applied efficiently [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ZnRA8D). Logistic regression can be used as a classic classifier to evaluate heart disease risk in a completely standalone method. Logistic regression can also be used to build as a meta-model in stacking ensemble algorithms in order to generate lifted predictions for inter-model predictions, generated from some based models [(Ganie et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?jPWoKR). In a logistic regression, one study found a model attained greater than neural models classifiers for predicting heart disease with a study accuracy of 91.65 % [(Ahmad et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?1pagEu).  
![][image8]  
*Figure 2.7 Logistic Regression Curve showing Probability of Valvular Heart Disease*

### **2.2.2 Overview of Deep Learning and why it matters in Cardiology**

Deep learning (DL) is a subcategory of machine learning (ML) that implements a stacked, layered and node-based framework, also known as artificial neural networks, that is inspired by the structure of the human brain. In healthcare, DL algorithms are powerful for processing large, complex data sets including images, audio, and signals like electrocardiograms (ECGs). DL algorithms can also extract features directly from the raw data, eliminating the complex manual features engineering process that is part of traditional ML workflows [(Z. Jiang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?dljkJp). They may also improve overall performance and diagnostic accuracy when used in conjunction with multi-modal data (e.g., images, text, audio), and integrate seamlessly into clinical workflows [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?gq1xhE). Common architectures used in healthcare practices include Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs), Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs), and Transformers, used for a number of tasks including image segmentation, image classification, and prediction of clinical outcomes [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?NnKHLz).

Three examples of healthcare applications of deep learning algorithms are:

### **2.2.2.1  Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs)**

CNNs are a type of deep neural network, that process visual data. CNNs process data in a grid-style manner and are adept at dealing with data for image classification, segmentation, and object detection [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?wJZeWk). In cardiology, CNNs can be used to process medical images such as echocardiograms, CT-scans, and CMR images in order to automate processes like view classification, segmentation of cardiac structures, and disease severity quantification [(L. Jiang et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0L0K48). CNNs can also be used for single-columns of data, like ECG signals or visual representations of heart sounds (phonocardiograms), to classify health states based on pattern recognition (e.g. identifying aortic stenosis, mitral regurgitation, or myocardial infarction) [(Ozturk et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Zr8NkC). The architecture’s local connectivity and weight sharing allows for the efficiency of extracting hierarchical features from raw data [(Talukdar & Singh, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?obK7aU).  
![][image9]  
*Figure 2.8 Standard CNN Architecture*

### **2.2.2.2  Recurrent Neural Networks (RNNs)**

RNNs are ideally suited to sequential data, where the order of the data is important. RNNs incorporate a feedback loop, so information can be stored as it is processed, which is beneficial in analysing time-series data signals, such as ECGs. One of the RNN based architectures is the Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) network, which also includes memory cells in addition to the RNN gating system (input, forget, output) that can solve the vanishing gradient during training process and can learn long-term relationships in your data. In healthcare applications of LSTMs, the classifies or recognize arrhythmias from the ECG signals, predict heart failure events based on sequential data from electronic health records, and analyse unique phonocardiogram signals to classify valvular heart disease identification patterns. Hybrid models have been created by combining CNNs for feature extraction and LSTMs for sequential processing.

### **2.2.2.2 Transformer Models**

Transformers is a new architecture that employs self-attention mechanism, to assign different weights to different parts of the data when making prediction for each sample [(Rahman et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0dCHBG). Assigning different weights to different parts of the data to model is a unique approach and allows for the model to learn relationships between distant parts of the data better than within an RNN framework. The design allows for maximum parallelization during training [(L. Jiang et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?pCuXkE). Transformers were originally created for natural language processing, but the architecture is now applied to computer vision (called Vision Transformers, or ViTs) and other data. One study analysed heart sounds with a Transformer and reported high accuracy rate, and the application of Transformer models are now being tested in ECG signal classification tasks and fusing modality data for comprehensive disease prediction [(Wu & Guo, 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?sLCwnL).

## **2.3 Role of PCG, ECG, and MRI in VHD Diagnosis**

### **2.3.1 Role of PCG in VHD Diagnosis**

Phonocardiography (PCG), which visually depicts heart sounds, represents an important non-invasive diagnostic approach for Valvular Heart Disease (VHD)  [(Santangelo et al., 2023; Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?umtQBs). PCG analysis typically consists of several steps, with filtering, segmentation, and normalization among the preprocessing methods used to improve the quality of the signal [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?SqnVAx). Once that is completed, features are extracted from the PCG signals. Features can be extracted from time-frequency domain of the PCG signal using methods such as Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients (MFCCs), Dual-Tree Complex Wavelet Transform (DTCWT), and wavelet scattering transforms [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?9YQ34O). These features, which capture the characteristics of heart sounds and murmurs associated with specific valve pathologies like aortic stenosis or mitral regurgitation, are then fed into machine learning (ML) or deep learning (DL) models for classification. Studies have successfully used algorithms such as Support Vector Machines (SVM), Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) models, and Convolutional Neural Networks (CNN) to distinguish between normal and abnormal heart sounds and to classify specific types of VHD [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?v5f8bh). One study used a ViT-based AI model that obtain features from raw PCG signals and achieved 99.9% diagnostic accuracy at identifying VHD. Another study used a deep learning model on raw heart sound data to identify various VHDs requiring intervention with high accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity [(Z. Jiang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?4IunI9).

An appeal of PCG is its relatively inexpensive use and non-invasive nature, allowing for feasibility as a screening tool, especially in limited-resource settings [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?pcz8T5). AI-powered auscultation can reduce both decrease in clinical proficiency of listening to heart sounds, and the variability with clinicians [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?QEX54R). AI-based digital stethoscopes have been able to classify VHD type with greater sensitivity than primary care providers [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Au7WNr). Nevertheless, limitations abound. Algorithms can be limited by the stethoscope used, or how the recordings were obtained (with noise attributed to patient movement, patient breathing, and ambient noise) [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?BPJmSP). Most research has focused on algorithm development rather than assessing disease severity, monitoring, or prognosis. Furthermore, there is a lack of large, standardized, and publicly available heart sound databases, which hinders the external validation and comparison of different algorithms [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?9h350s). Finally, the “black box” characteristics of some AI can create barriers to clinical trust, and explainability when used in clinical practice  [(Sengupta et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?rThdlc).

### **2.3.2      Role of ECG in VHD Diagnosis**

The electrocardiogram (ECG) is a relevant, non-invasive, and inexpensive modality in the diagnosis journey of valvular heart disease (VHD)  [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?SropKl). Reliability of standard ECG interpretation as a means of diagnosing a specific valve disease is limited but it can show evidence of structural heart anomalies that are often a result of VHD. For example, left ventricular hypertrophy on an ECG gives some indication pertained to the presence of aortic stenosis, which causes left ventricular remodeling [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Q7DiEz). Most recently there has been an application of artificial intelligence (AI), namely deep learning (DL), where the diagnostic potential of ECG for VHD has increased dramatically [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?kjeo1a). Specifically investigators have designed DL algorithms, in the form of Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) using large cohorts of ECGs linked with echocardiograms for determining individual valvular lesions, and large datasets of ECGs paired with echocardiograms to detect specific valvular lesions [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?nuz2l5). By detecting subtle ECG waveform patterns that cannot be seen with human eye, these AI algorithms can generate prediction of moderate to severe aortic stenosis (AS), aortic regurgitation (AR), and mitral regurgitation (MR) with credible performance accuracy. For example, a recent AI-ECG study offered an area under the curve (AUROC) of 0.88 for AS, 0.83 for MR, and 0.77 for AR  (Elias et al., 2022). AI-ECG models could be a viable referral tool to identify patients at high risk to refer to Echocardiogram studies for diagnosis [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?lSxoWu).

However, ECG has limitations in diagnosing VHD in practice. One major problem with AI-ECG models is the high false positivity rate, resulting in a low positive predictive value (PPV), particularly when screening the general population with a low prevalence of VHD [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?yHBOzW). While these models have a high negative predictive value, meaning they are effective at ruling out significant VHD, the high number of false positives could lead to unnecessary downstream investigations [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?juar1z). Also, AI algorithms perform data capture outside the experiments, e.g. elderly expressing QRS complexes or bundle branch blocks (Elias et al., 2022). Also, the explainability of models is still a big puzzle, especially for specific ECG features the aliases are utilizing to make predictions but further, that is affecting clinical trust [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?EkyrNA).Finally, generalizability in applications between different health institutions with ECG applications, performance has been shown to increase before transfers to providers’ cohorts [(Li et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?2a1Tqc). So, while AI-ECG has much potential, prospective validation is needed to optimize clinical utility and cost-effectiveness [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?z7tmTw).

### **2.3.3  Role of MRI in VHD Diagnosis**

Cardiovascular Magnetic Resonance (CMR) imaging is the criterion or gold standard for specific measurements in the diagnosis of Valvular Heart Disease (VHD) due to its high spatial resolution and multi-planarity [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?kw6qb0). The main advantage of CMR is the accurate and reproducible quantification of cardiac chamber volumes, biventricular function, and blood flow which are critical in assessing the hemodynamic effects of VHD [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?tfZUsT). For example, in patients with aortic regurgitation (AR), CMR is considered the gold standard for severity quantification, especially because measurement is performed with a single volume, unlike traditional 2D echocardiography. In cases of eccentric or multiple regurgitant jets the accuracy of CMR as the gold standard would be instrumental to determine the severity of VHD [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?cn9jpP). The CMR with AI has also greatly improved the evaluation of VHD through automated calculations of volumes and function. This automated process highly reduces the time that is needed to make the calculations individually by hand [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?K0RqZx). Additionally, CMR is the gold standard of myocardial tissue characterization, also allowing for quantification of myocardial fibrosis via late gadolinium enhancement (LGE). This is an important marker of prognosis in terms of aortic stenosis (AS) [(Talukdar & Singh, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?NG9qlV). This process is important for risk stratification and aids in assessing the optimal timing for procedures such as aortic valve replacement (AVR).

While CMR has many benefits, there are a few limitations to CMR that restrict its use in diagnosing VHD [(L. Jiang et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?KBiEN0). One key limitation is that the scan time, relative to other imaging modalities, is very long due to acquiring multiple sequences and therefore requires compensation for cardiac and respiratory motion  [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?BsImyF). Scan time could be prohibitive for some patients. Another limitation is the recurring use of gadolinium-based contrast agents to complete myocardial tissue characterization – this is contraindicated in patients with renal dysfunctions [(Talukdar & Singh, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?IVHUI3). Lastly, costs, along with the less availability of CMR compared to echocardiography, make it unsuitable as a first-line imaging tool [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?rLTDlk). Fortunately, studies have gained momentum regarding counteractive strategies for these limitations. For example, a study has also demonstrated that deep learning algorithms can reduce scan times to approximately one-fifth of the original time by improving parallel imaging and correcting motion artifacts [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?97nke8). In one study, a deep learning model accurately reconstructed virtual LGE equivalent images without the need for gadolinium administration, and readers rated its quality as better than that of traditional LGE standard images. These studies suggest that AI can help expand its use and overcome some limitations of CMR in the VHD diagnostic process [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?HbLxw6).

### **2.3.4 Justification for PCG only approach in VHD Diagnosis**

Recent innovations in artificial intelligence (AI) have improved non-invasive cardiovascular diagnostics significantly, particularly in electrocardiography (ECG) and cardiovascular magnetic resonance (CMR) imaging [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?noSfTy). AI-generated ECG analysis can detect numerous conditions automatically, including arrhythmias and structurally based heart diseases, such as aortic stenosis, at times more accurately than a clinician can [(Wu & Guo, 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?6UrXOY). Similarly, CMR, which is the gold-standard for evaluating cardiac structure and function, has also leveraged AI to automate ventricular function measurements, halve scan time, and create virtual contrast enhancement without using gadolinium [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?uX1xhH). However, there are some limitations: AI-ECG may have challenges with generalisability with varying health systems/populations (at times) and older or conduction abnormal patients[(Santangelo et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?baSRYq). CMR tends to be costly, lengthy, and less accessible than other more routine tests.

Despite these advanced imaging and electrical methods, there is a strong rationale for a fresh look at phonocardiography (PCG), i.e., evaluation of heart sounds [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?2ExMfN). PCG is non-invasive, low-cost, and very portable so it is ideal for mass screening application use, tel-medicine, and use in resource-limited settings where ECG or CMR would not be appropriate [(Talukdar & Singh, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0XlBY3). AI has also been applied to PCG for detecting valvular and congenital heart diseases with greater than 90% accuracy, but very little work in this modality has been accomplished due to issues of ambient noise and the next to impossible identification of large quality-standardized public datasets [(Wu & Guo, 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?vq6V8r). 

VHD is often an underdiagnosed condition until advanced stages, and effective auscultation skills are lost or minimal in most clinicians. Millions of individual patients would benefit from a reliable AI PCG only diagnostic framework, as this is a major unmet need in clinical practice [(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?2RnsUk). There are good reasons to study those focused truly on PCG to create a mediated/validated AI-derived, more sophisticated any-utilized PCG diagnostic tool to leverage PCG imaging modalities that would appeal to practice as a preliminary/threshold detection method of heart sounds for a clinical diagnostic valuation.

## **2.4 Existing ML/DL Models for VHD Prediction**

The field of Artificial Intelligence (AI) models for the diagnosis of cardiovascular and valvular heart disease (VHD) has been characterized by rapid advances, superior performance metrics, and an existing trend to using multimodal data. A review of studies suggests AI models (both ML and DL) achieved high accuracy levels, commonly above 90%, with some even reaching 98-99%, for specialized cases [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?FrYv9n). There is a significant trend that ensemble and DL models, especially those that include multimodal data (e.g., ECG, and PCG, and/or clinical data) outperform single modality classifiers. Models employing XGBoost and variations of CNN architectures, and hybrid systems including CNN-LSTMs are often in the top performing groups demonstrating consistent success in modeling the underlying complex nonlinearities in cardiovascular data [(Rahman et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ZjjaPl).

One of the major benefits derived from the studies was the ability for AI to greatly improve diagnostic accuracy and efficiency. For example, DL models can detect VHD from raw heart sounds, or ECGs at often comparable or better sensitivity and specificity than clinicians using stethoscope based auscultation [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?mmCDh8). Jiang et al. (2024) and Al-Issa & Alqudah (2022) reported accuracies of  \>98%, for classifying certain valve disease types, using phonocardiograms (PCGs). These results show the capabilities of some architectures, like CNN-LSTM, rely on temporal acoustic inputs [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023; Z. Jiang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Y8HVkH). Likewise, multimodal models utilizing ECG, PCG, and clinical records data show consistent improvements over unimodal models. This is especially advantageous, as models develop a more comprehensive model of a patient’s health state linking electrical (ECG) and mechanical (PCG) processes of the heart, thereby reducing false positives and increasing robustness [(Hangaragi et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?fX5N3B).

Nonetheless, one major and common limitation seems to be an occurrence of the “black box” problem, whereby the decision-making of complex DL models is not transparent [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?q2Rfsv). Loss of interpretability is a considerable barrier to clinical deployment, as clinicians are not willing to have confidence in their recommendation without a transparent pathophysiological mechanism [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?8eCpF4). There is work being done to implement techniques such as SHAP and saliency maps to help provide ways to interpret the model's predictions, but reliability is debated and doesn't fully address the problem [(Ganie et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?CUfuyY). Another limitation is the false positive rate with screening applications, particularly under low disease prevalence. Several ECG-based models had excellent negative predictive value and poor positive predictive value, which would lead to unnecessary downstream testing and patient discomfort [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Mzo3KU).

Also, the limitations of performance and generalizability of these models are bound by data-related limitations. Most studies are trained on small, often retrospective, single-center cohorts which are unlikely to represent from various populations leading to decreases in performance after external validation [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?rYdgR3). The lack of sufficiently large public databases hinders the possibilities for systematic benchmarking algorithms [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?DWrGiQ). Class imbalance is also a frequently significant limitation preventing cohorts from biasing the models toward more likely to have conditions thereby lowering accuracy on class with rarer diseases [(Zhang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?fmpUds). While techniques like SMOTE can mitigate this, the underlying data limitations remain a fundamental challenge [(Ogunpola et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?meFWnj). here are also consistent threats to model robustness such as inter-observer variability in echocardiographic labeling, heterogeneous data acquisition (stethoscope, etc.), and data-set shift over time [(Zhang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?wYzgWd).

Going forward, the trend will continue toward more advanced multimodal approaches combined with federated learning methods to resolve limitations. Federated learning can address data privacy and potential data scarcity by training models across institutions using federated learning, without sharing raw patient data [(Alasmari et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?gOSeRi). The overall goal is to develop the end to end DL processes related to raw, unprocessed data which will gain us more authentic clinical settings without more difficult labor-intensive manual feature engineering [(Z. Jiang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?CoBSMz). However, for these potent AI tools to be valuable in routine care, future studies must emphasize clinical trials prospectively, external validation on various populations, and the development of sound, explainable AI (XAI) mechanisms to harvest trust and accomplish equitable and efficacious patient care [(Ganie et al., 2025; Zhang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Ngij37).

### **2.4.1 Performance Trends by Modality**

Artificial Intelligence (AI) models across multiple data modalities for screening, diagnosing, and managing cardiovascular and valvular heart diseases (VHD) have varying performance trajectories depending on the signal modality employed, such as phonocardiogram (PCG), electrocardiogram (ECG), imaging modalities such as MRI, or multi-modal approaches which combined signals.

### **2.4.1.1 Phonocardiogram (PCG)**

PCG models have high accuracy when detecting VHD [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?xgWAmN). Models used on PCG signals, which represents a heart sound such as heart murmurs, are usually on specific conditions, e.g., aortic stenosis (AS), mitral regurgitation (MR), mitral stenosis (MS), and mitral valve prolapse (MVP) [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?5vX31t). For example, one light-weight hybrid CNN-LSTM model had 98.5% and 99.87% accuracy on non-augmented and augmented datasets, respectively, for a five-class VHD problem [(Al-Issa & Alqudah, 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?8MBBoJ). A study using a Vision Transformer (ViT)-based AI model on raw PCG signals stated a diagnostic accuracy of 99.9% in diagnosing VHD [(L. Jiang et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?kCV7St). TThe quality of murmur classification would be a real strength for PCG models since a mild-to-moderate murmur is the common classification for valvular dysfunction [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?3sHBJk). Performance and accuracy can be sensitive to the quality of the heart sound recording, and reject patient movement, breathing, or even the stethoscope itself as noise [(El-Sofany et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?6qBdcy). Most of the pool of research runs theoretical algorithms, but a majority lack easy access to a sufficient number of public high-quality datasets, making systematic comparison difficult [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?n1zriq).

### **2.4.1.2  Electrocardiogram (ECG)**

AI-facilitated ECG interpretation has become an effective and efficient way to screen for VHD and other types of structural heart disease [(Talukdar & Singh, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?MdcXRK). Specifically, deep learning-based models, and Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) can recognize subtle traits in the ECG signal waveforms that the human eye cannot detect when applied to screening for AS, AR, and MR [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?xGSEUc). Multiple studies have indicated good performance with Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve (AUROC) values ranging between 0.77 to 088 for detecting individual left-sided valves lesions [(Wu & Guo, 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?hbSeA8). An advantage to the ECG is its low cost and universal availability to apply screening studies at scale. However, one of the major limitations of the ECG is the significant high false positive rate; therefore, the positive predictive value (PPV) is low, especially when the prevalence of disease is low [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?MTV2YQ). For instance, one model had a PPV of 10% for AS but had a negative predictive value (PPV) of 99% [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?EyabmW). The model performance is also lower for older patients and patients with conduction abnormalities such as bundle branch block  [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?72nvD2).

### **2.4.1.3  Cardiac Imaging (MRI, CT, Echocardiography)**

AI uses for cardiac imaging are particularly suited for automating tasks that require substantial training and are labor intensive [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?YGa2Zz). In echocardiography, artificial intelligence (AI) can carry out labeling, assess quality and provide measurements on cardiac chamber size and function all with similar or improved accuracy than performing manual measurements [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?8ucTEF),  and there are models developed that can assess the degree of AS and MR from echocardiographic photos/videos with high accuracy [(Wu & Guo, 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?29q1a4). AI can similarly handle segmentation and evaluate left ventricular size and function, and even provide virtually contrast-enhanced images using the native images without gadolinium, in CMR, and CT images [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?cpZaTM). An artificial intelligence pipeline using CT images was used to develop patient specific models of AS hemodynamics, with the dynamics in the models corresponding to clinical Doppler measurements [(Ozturk et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?lRVFL2). These imaging methods likely have little to add for initial, population screening compared to PCG or ECG, due to cost and availability [(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?UzFmuk). Finally, Fractal analysis approaches applied to CMR and echocardiographic images have been proposed as a measure of the complexity of myocardial structures, proposed to uncover subtle underlying issues in disease states, like the presence of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?eRamQW).

### **2.4.2 Explainable AI for VHD Prediction**

Multiple studies have implemented explainable AI (XAI) techniques to increase the interpretability of the models built for Valvular Heart Disease (VHD) prediction. Kwon et al. (2020) used a saliency map to show where parts of the ECG (i.e. the T-wave) was most influential in predicting aortic stenosis [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?MnL0ac). Cohen-Shelly et al. (2021) utilized a saliency map with a CNN model, which showed the TP segment of the ECG being valued most in the prediction [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?eUCbMX). El-Sofany et al. (2024) applied SHAP (SHapley Additive Explanations) to explain their XGBoost model of heart disease prediction, explaining how the system reached its eventual output [(Talukdar & Singh, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?inxmUt). Ganie et al. (2025) also employed SHAP to allow insights and transparency on how predictor variables contribute to the heart disease prediction for their ensemble models [(Ganie et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?vx64E2). Oliveira (2024) displayed both Gradient-weighted Class Activation Mapping (Grad-CAM) and SHAP to explain the predictions of the model created from the multimodal ECG and PCG data indicating how the main QRS complex in ECGs and S1/S2 sounds in PCGs were important contributions. Lastly, Rahman et al. (2024) indicated that the self-attention aspect of their transformer model provided interpretability by “attending” to the input features assigned to the attention weights, so that clinicians would know which data were the most important to the predictions of their models [(Rahman et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?DIb31e).

The XAI techniques represent different routes for pharmacists to navigate the potentially “black box” features of complicated AI models. SHAP (SHapley Additive Explanations) is a leading method that is built on game theory that generates a value of importance contribution for every feature directed to a specific prediction [(Ganie et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?jRsjLG).They can be visualized using different types of plots such as waterfall plots that show how the sum of every feature either pushes the model output from a baseline and the counterfactual features giving rise to the final prediction and force plots that are visual representations of the features that push for or restrict a specific prediction [(Ganie et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ZSS3W8). Saliency maps and Grad-CAM are visualization methods that are often discussed with neural networks and particularly image or signal data input such as ECGs [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0ovdsu). aliency maps and Grad-CAM produce heatmaps that highlight what part(s) of the input (e.g. ECG waves/segments) was valued most for the resulting model decision [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?FuNjwo). Although these methods allow transparency and give confidence, on the other hand, some sources suggest there is limited reliability, thus not a rational or persuasive pathophysiologic explanation for how the model reasoned [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?p3DtTG).

## **2.5 Feature Extraction Techniques**

Feature extraction is a critical stage in biomedical data analysis, particularly for developing accurate machine learning (ML) and deep learning (DL) models for diagnosing Valvular Heart Disease (VHD) [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?3bHGcJ). This process involves transforming raw, often complex, data from modalities like phonocardiograms (PCG), electrocardiograms (ECG), or medical images into a set of derived numerical values, known as features [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?xyOD7e). These features are designed to capture the most relevant and discriminative information while reducing redundancy and computational complexity (Spencer [et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0GCe6e).   
In the context of VHD, this is crucial because raw signals from sources like PCG are non-stationary and can be corrupted by noise from patient movement, breathing, and the environment, making direct analysis difficult [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Ubpojc). By extracting meaningful features, algorithms can more effectively identify the subtle patterns associated with specific valve pathologies, such as the unique characteristics of murmurs in aortic stenosis (AS) or mitral regurgitation (MR) [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?LWT1Ba).

The choice of feature extraction technique is highly dependent on the data modality and the specific diagnostic goal. For PCG signals, which represent heart sounds, time-frequency domain analysis is a common and effective approach [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?FgE63G).
