Methods such as Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients (MFCCs) and Dual-Tree Complex Wavelet Transform (DTCWT) are frequently used because they can efficiently represent the non-stationary properties of heart sounds and murmurs [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?BQJapN).   
One study successfully combined MFCC with DTCWT coefficients to create a representative feature vector for classifying different types of VHD [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?d0d8fS). Other advanced techniques include wavelet scattering transforms [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?UWCuC3) and higher-order spectral analysis, which can extract more subtle features that are significantly better at differentiating pathologies than lower-order methods like the short-time Fourier transform [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?y3BHpk). This extraction step allows models to focus on physiologically relevant characteristics, like the timing, shape, and frequency of a murmur, which are critical for distinguishing between normal and abnormal heart sounds [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?pSmGFi).

Ultimately, the quality of feature extraction directly influences the performance of the final classification model [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?oFvVfo). Studies have shown that selecting the most statistically significant and relevant features can increase prediction accuracy, reduce model overfitting, and lower computational costs [(Al-Mahdi et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?LxKRxp). For instance, a study on heart disease prediction found that various feature selection methods, such as chi-squared testing and Relief, identified chest pain type (cp), exercise-induced angina (exang), and ST depression (oldpeak) as the most influential features from clinical datasets [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?UhT9gX). This process of identifying and isolating the most impactful variables helps create more efficient and robust diagnostic systems [(Al-Mahdi et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?XTNAg6). In VHD research, the feature extraction stage has been described as a key step for creating effective models [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?dBGzjb), with different studies demonstrating that various approaches can achieve comparable performance by successfully isolating the critical characteristics of heart sounds [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?try3Mu). This underscores that a well-designed feature extraction process is fundamental to translating raw biomedical data into clinically actionable insights for VHD diagnosis [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?5xCokj).

### **2.5.1 Fractal-based Feature Extraction Techniques**

Fractal analysis offers a powerful mathematical tool for quantifying complex spatial and temporal patterns found in biological signals like the phonocardiogram (PCG) and electrocardiogram (ECG) [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?OrDdMi). These methods are based on fractal geometry, which measures the 'complexity' of a pattern through a unitless number called the fractal dimension (FD) [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?VPKwnj). A key principle is self-similarity, where a pattern appears equally detailed regardless of the scale at which it is examined [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?G8aRqL). For a time-series signal like an ECG or PCG, fractal analysis identifies features such as self-similarity, power-law scaling, and scale invariance. Techniques like the box-counting method can be used to calculate the FD of a structure, such as myocardial trabeculae in an image, by measuring how the number of boxes needed to cover the structure changes with the size of the boxes. This approach can be applied to virtually any pattern type, including textures, contours, and time-series data from digital signals [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?5grljC).

The application of fractal analysis to cardiovascular signals includes the broader category of radiomics, which involves extracting complex patterns and characteristics from medical images [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?jum5as). Fractal analysis is used to extract features from signals by quantifying their complexity and self-similarity over different scales [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?csVXeE). For instance, one major application is in analyzing heart rate variability from ECG recordings, where a loss of variability, or 'decomplexification,' can predict higher mortality [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?vn0Isg). Three primary fractal methods are described for this purpose: power spectrum density (PSD) analysis, which characterizes power-law scaling in the frequency domain; detrended fluctuation analysis (DFA), which measures correlations across timescales in the time domain; and multifractal analysis, which assumes different parts of a signal have different local regularities and FDs [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?kQ5GdX).

The practical applications of fractal analysis in cardiology are extensive. In PCG analysis, fractal-based methods have been used to create features for machine learning models to detect valvular heart disease [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?8PnxKB). For example, fractal feature analysis has been used on echocardiographic images to automatically detect myocardial infarction by measuring surface roughness as an FD [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?bZqUjS). In another application, fractal analysis of cardiac MRI scans helped quantify left ventricular trabeculae, revealing that the FD of these structures varies with ethnicity, hypertension, and body mass index and can help detect subtle abnormalities in conditions like hypertrophic cardiomyopathy [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?qPXLR5).   
For ECGs, fractal indices from heart rate variability have demonstrated prognostic value, with specific fractal exponents predicting sudden cardiac death in the elderly and deterioration in dilated cardiomyopathy. Researchers suggest that incorporating these fractal indices into risk-scoring systems could refine patient selection for treatments like implantable defibrillators.

### **2.5.2 Limitations of Fractal-based Feature Extraction Techniques**

While there are many strengths and potential applications of fractal-based feature extraction in biomedical contexts, there are also several significant limitations that must be addressed for these methods to be clinically useful and widely adopted [(Sengupta et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?pqH8jb). A primary challenge is the "black box" nature of many algorithms that use fractal features, particularly complex ones like deep learning models [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?lJQApv). Clinicians may find it difficult to trust or implement a system if its decision-making process is not transparent or easily understandable. This lack of interpretability can create a barrier to adoption, as the statistical associations identified by the model might not have a clear, convincing pathophysiological explanation to support widespread clinical use [(Ganie et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?sQIYQy).

Another set of limitations arises from the mathematical and methodological assumptions inherent in fractal analysis. One key issue is that the linear nature of some fractal techniques, such as Principal Component Analysis (PCA), may make them a poor fit for certain applications, leading to poor performance [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?rZDezf). For instance, one study found that PCA-based feature extraction performed very poorly in diagnosing valvular heart disease from phonocardiography signals compared to other methods [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Q1GPiF). Furthermore, for fractal analysis to be reliable, many aspects of data acquisition and post-processing, such as the specific algorithm used for segmentation, mask size, and grid ranges, must be carefully specified and standardized, as these can significantly affect the computed fractal dimension [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?1J9nrH). This sensitivity to initial parameters can make it challenging to compare results across different studies and settings.

Finally, there are practical and data-related challenges that constrain the application of fractal analysis in real-world clinical scenarios [(L. Jiang et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0Wx4HI). The algorithms are often sensitive to the type of equipment used (e.g., different stethoscopes) and the quality of the data, with the same algorithm potentially producing different results from signals obtained from varied devices [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ZTnAXt).   
The scarcity of large, high-quality, and comprehensive public databases also poses a significant challenge, making it difficult to compare algorithms systematically and address data imbalances [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ZirWUo). Most existing studies have focused on theoretical algorithms rather than practical clinical applications, and there is a need for rigorous, repeatable, and validated methods before these tools can be securely deployed for patient care [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?K0P0J2). Additionally, many medical dataset features can be irrelevant or intercorrelated, which may cause overfitting in predictive models during classification tasks [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?sUleIu).

### **2.5.3 Signal Processing and Machine Learning Feature Extraction Techniques**

In addition to fractal analysis, there are several other sophisticated signal processing and machine learning techniques for extracting meaningful features from biomedical signals, particularly phonocardiograms (PCGs) and electrocardiograms (ECGs) [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?7JMlBY).   
One prominent family of methods is time-frequency analysis, which transforms a one-dimensional time-domain signal into a two-dimensional representation showing how the signal's frequency content changes over time [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?PKTIHW). Techniques include the short-time Fourier transform (STFT), which analyzes small, windowed segments of a signal, and various wavelet transforms, such as the continuous wavelet transform (CWT), discrete wavelet transform (DWT), and the dual-tree complex wavelet transform (DTCWT) [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?m6jxAH). These methods are particularly effective for non-stationary signals like PCGs because they offer good resolution in both time and frequency domains.   
Another important technique, borrowed from speech processing, is the Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients (MFCCs), which represent the short-term power spectrum of a sound and reflect the non-linear way the human ear perceives frequency [(Z. Jiang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?vhi7td). There are also methods like principal component analysis (PCA) for dimensionality reduction, various entropy measures (e.g., Shannon entropy) [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?688kts), and deep learning approaches like convolutional neural networks (CNNs) that can automatically learn and extract features from raw data or their visual representations (e.g., spectrograms) without manual engineering [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?5vqD50).

### **2.5.4 Differences between the Feature Extraction Techniques**

The primary difference between the signal processing and machine learning techniques and fractal techniques lies in the type of information they are designed to extract [(Poterucha et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?zPbv56). Time-frequency and wavelet analyses are fundamentally concerned with decomposing a signal into its constituent frequencies and observing how these frequencies evolve over time [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?TnMPmM). They excel at identifying specific events, such as the S1 and S2 heart sounds or murmurs [(Abdessater et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?CAozHg), and characterizing their spectral properties like pitch and energy distribution [(Khan et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?VT58fj). Similarly, MFCCs are designed to capture the perceptual characteristics of a sound signal [(Al-Shannaq et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?L2pMcn).   
In contrast, fractal analysis does not focus on specific frequencies but rather quantifies the overall 'complexity' or 'roughness' of a signal across multiple scales [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?xkP0N6). It operates on the principle of self-similarity, measuring how a pattern's detail changes with the level of magnification [(Poterucha et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?fAn40d). While wavelets can localize events in time and frequency, fractal dimension provides a single, holistic measure of a signal's structural complexity, which has been linked to underlying physiological states like cardiac autonomic function or myocardial fibrosis [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?JoeliD).

In terms of application and performance, these signal processing and machine learning techniques can be complementary but also have distinct strengths and weaknesses. For tasks like heart sound segmentation and identifying specific murmur characteristics (e.g., timing, shape), wavelet and time-frequency methods are highly effective [(Rahman et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?OYDVx8). They provide the features needed for models to classify different types of valvular heart disease with high accuracy. However, the performance of traditional signal processing methods can be limited if certain assumptions about the signal are not met, and they often require careful, manual selection of features [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?faBVl6). Deep learning models like CNNs can overcome this by learning features automatically from time-frequency maps [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?1nf2zH). However, they often function as "black boxes," meaning their decision-making processes can be difficult for clinicians to understand or trust [(Sengupta et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ijzGqr).

Fractal analysis, while powerful for characterizing systemic complexity, can be sensitive to data acquisition parameters and may not be as effective for localizing specific, transient events within a signal [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?veH0nY). One study on diagnosing valvular heart disease from PCG signals noted that PCA-based feature extraction performed very poorly compared to other methods, suggesting that linear techniques may be a bad fit for the non-linear characteristics of some biomedical signals [(Spencer et al., 2020\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?aR7oQb). Ultimately, the choice of method depends on the specific clinical question: time-frequency and wavelet methods are ideal for event detection and spectral characterization, whereas fractal analysis is better suited for quantifying the global, scale-invariant complexity of physiological systems [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?8FBxji).

## **2.6 Summary of Reviewed Literature**

As described by the reviewed studies, the detection and diagnosis of Valvular Heart Disease (VHD) is changing from a more traditional clinical exam to data based artificial intelligence (AI) approach [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?TTDOuR). It is well-established that VHD is a growing global health issue, particularly in aging populations, yet it remains frequently underdiagnosed and undertreated [(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?dQiQIj). Physically auscultating heart sounds initially remains a well-known approach, but it largely lacks robustness, detecting significant VHD with sensitivities as poor as 40-70%, and even that rate is variable by clinician experience and certain valve lesion [(Davidsen et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?owjgSk). Echocardiography is the gold standard for diagnosing VHD, and while highly effective, its associated costs and requirements for trained personnel and diverse modalities, can limit its potential for widespread screening [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?iF9zKm). The gap in reliable, accurate, and accessible screening modalities has led to extensive investigation for VHD screening alternatives. AI models for VHD screening incorporating different data modalities are demonstrating a lot of potential [(Santangelo et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?oGX126).

Machine learning (ML) and deep learning (DL) model applications suggest that various data modalities can identify screening techniques for VHD with high performance [(Jaltotage et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?kjWvhP). ML and DL models using phonocardiogram (PCG) signals from digital stethoscopes appears to outperform physician auscultation. For example, although many of the studies for PCG signals did not include diagnostic testing of ecology or stenosis, they reported model performance with up to 98% of continuous data to differentiate normal versus abnormal heart sounds, and specific values including AS and MR [(Al-Issa & Alqudah, 2022\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?sbBmw1). AI-powered electrocardiogram (ECG) analysis has similarly emerged as a potent screening method. Deep learning (DL) models can identify subtle patterns in the ECGs that are not evident to the human eye to identify patients with valvular heart disease (VHD), frequently achieving high diagnostic accuracy with AUROC values ranging from 0.80 to 0.91 [(Sengupta et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?gt28qQ). Cardiac imaging, such as CT and MRI, is now being facilitated by AI of all forms; the automation of complex tasks surrounding aortic root segmentation for TAVR (transcatheter aortic valve replacement) planning and fibrosis quantification are streamlined and made more reproducible [(L. Jiang et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?ISHpFC). Another common observation is that most AI-ECG models generally demonstrate high negative predictive value, allowing for ideal rule-out of disease, but demonstrates lower positive predictive value which results in false positive observation in low prevalence populations [(Bamford et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Dnt7Bs).

A common and powerful trend across the body of literature is the utility of multimodal models, those that utilize data from multiple modalities at once (ECG, PCG, clinical records, imaging, etc) [(Wu & Guo, 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?EPHi1j). These fusion models consistently outperform single-modality approaches by creating a more comprehensive and robust patient profile [(van Assen et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?Ox1c5y). For example, even correlated ECG and PCG signals, utilizes a model that is able to leverage both electrical activity and mechanical activity of the heart, thus achieving higher accuracy than classifying them as normal or abnormal [(Wu & Guo, 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?0OMFnO). Ensemble learning is also frequently used to maximize performance in multilabel models with variation of stacking and voting types of methods, leveraging the models complementary advantages. Performance exceeds \>95% accuracy [(Ganie et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?vwWsgO). Unsupervised learning is also very helpful in phenomapping patients into identifiable patient subgroups with non-uniform risk profiles and prognoses that have not yet been recognized using traditional classification type methods, and will further personalize medicine [(Sengupta et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?UPB5jr).

Notwithstanding reported performance metrics, there is a common barrier in all studies. One major hurdle to clinical adoption is the black box phenomenon of some complex DL models inhibiting clinical interpretation as well as clinician sounding credible [(Ainiwaer et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?B7rxLd). Iare observing more suggestions regarding using explainable AI (XAI) as in SHAP, Grad-CAM to gain insights into the models [(Ganie et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?UFfdzY). Data needs continue to be a major issue where many of their models are trained on small datasets that are retrospective or single-center only, which brings inevitable generalizability issues as well as demographics of the experiment, including sample size for age, sex, and race [(Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?c7VScC). Therefore, the literature strongly suggests that future efforts should focus on prospective evidence in diverse real-world populations as well as developing strong, transparent, ethically sound AI tools to fully realize these promising technologies into improving patient-centric care [(Canning et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?SsM483).  
Deep learning models, which are a subset of machine learning, are widely utilized for feature extraction for valvular heart disease (VHD) prediction by using raw data to produce derived values to minimize redundancy [(Kannan et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?NiUMva). A study incorporating a model based on deep learning applied to raw heart sound data was successfully able to identify numerous types of VHD needing intervention and produced features such as Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients (MFCCs) and root-mean-square energy [(Z. Jiang et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?cN5K9Z). Fractal analysis is an additional mathematical approach which seeks to “quantify” complex biological patterns from medical images, using images such as echocardiograms, by determining fractal dimensions. Fractal analysis has been used to assess myocardial tissue injury and the complexity of trabeculae in still images [(Captur et al., 2017\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?R0qjOv). Considering its potential non-invasive and objective measure of heart muscle injury for patients with VHD, its use can be recommended.

##  **2.5 Research Gaps** 

1. Absence of Prospective Clinical Trials & Cost-effectiveness Analyses: Most studies utilizing AI for VHD screening and diagnosis have relied on retrospective datasets, limiting real-world relevance. Prospective clinical trials are required to determine clinical efficacy of these AI technologies and whether they truly enhance patient outcomes prior to incorporation into clinical guidelines. [(e.g., Canning et al., 2023; Talukdar & Singh, 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?G3QSBe).  
     
2. Generalizability and Performance in Diverse Populations: Predominantly, AI models are developed with data from a single institution raising questions of generalizability and bias when applied to different populations. It is critical that Ivalidate these models externally using diverse populations that include variances in race, ethnicity, and location to ensure models 1\) perform and 2\) do not contribute to health inequities. (e.g., [Ainiwaer et al., 2023; Messika-Zeitoun et al., 2023\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?UIvd60)  
     
3. Limited Research on Disease Severity/ Prognosis: Most current research focuses on the binary classification of auscultation sounds/signals as being “normal” or “abnormal,” rather than addressing more nuanced clinical questions. Additional studies that use AI to assess disease severity, predict disease trajectory, and following interventions for outcomes monitoring remotely are greatly needed. (e.g., [Abdessater et al., 2025; Kannan et al., 2025; Sengupta et al., 2024\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?O3OATC)  
     
4. Lack of Standardized, High-quality Datasets: The creation of safe, solid, usable AI auscultation and prediction algorithms are limited by the lack of large, high-quality and public heart sound databases. The databases that exist can vary in recording equipment and methods, making it hard to compare algorithms, thus creating a large standardized database to serve as a foundation for future intelligent heart sound studies is stipulated as a essential for future AI heart sound investigation. (e.g., [Bamford et al., 2024; El-Sofany et al., 2024; Ganie et al., 2025; L. Jiang et al., 2025\)](https://www.zotero.org/google-docs/?djdftq)  
 


   # **3\. Chapter 3**

## **3.1  Introduction**

This chapter outlines the methodological pipeline that originated from a systematic merger of various methods to create a rigorous and explainable phonocardiogram (PCG)-based language model for valvular heart disease (VHD) classification. The design is sequential, having the order of reliability in data, feature, model, and interpretability. The overall method was influenced by the challenges established from literature reviews of the PCG modeling process including but not limited to noise sensitivity, small dataset size, class imbalance, and lack of interpretability in other PCG models.

The methodology was organized into eight order dependent phases. Phase 1 involves the collection of a PCG dataset and all preprocessing steps including normalization, segmentation and augmentation. Phase 2 outlines double-threaded feature extraction, deep features from CNNs applied to Mel-spectrograms and fractal and entropy-based features as a measure of complexity from the signal. Phase 3 describes feature scaling and dimensionality reduction using Principal Component Analysis (PCA) but separate training, validation, and test transformations will be used to avoid feature and class leakage.

Phase 4 provides machine learning models derived, trained, and evaluated using RandomizedSearchCV. Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) to be ran with deep-only, fractal-only, and deep/fractal fused feature bases. Phase 5 includes model fusion with stacking and attention mechanisms as a method of training a model ensemble to improve generalizability. Phase 6 presents the evaluation model with a comprehensive evaluation process for the model using performance measures and statistical tests to allow out precise evaluation model evaluation. Phase 7 outlines, model explainability, each model was described, modeled explainability through global and local XAI methods, such as SHAP based analyses, and modeled visualizations, while Phase 8 synthesizes all the outcomes to be an interpretable manner connecting modeled features to clinical perceptions.

This pipeline not only provides predictive utility, but also made simultaneously interpretable, and clinically relevant as such can be introduced for use both within research and also low-resource health-care.

## **3.2  System Architecture**

The system architecture proposed for PCG-based valvular heart disease prediction is organized as a sequential pipeline with distinct phases that address specific issues pertaining to processing, feature engineering, classification, and interpretability. The workflow as a whole is presented as illustrated in Figure 3.1. 

On input, the PCG data from the CirCor DigiScope dataset are pairwise concatenated and subjected to preprocessing steps (i.e. amplitude normalization; bandpass filtering; segmentation into fixed-length windows; and data augmentation) which render the signals homogenous, limit noise, and decrease class imbalance.

Next, each of the preprocessed signals are passed into two independent extractor pathways in parallel. In the first pathway, segments are transformed and then processed by a pre-trained convolutional neural network (CNN) to convert the segments into a Mel-spectrogram image and obtain high-dimensional deep features of PCG. In the second pathway, a series of fractal and entropy-based measures (i.e. Higuchi fractal dimension, Katz fractal dimension, Petrosian fractal dimension, detrended fluctuation analysis, Hurst exponent, approximate and sample entropy) are applied to capture the intrinsic complexity and irregularity of the heart sounds.

From there, both sets of features are standardized using a z-score, and concatenated into a single feature space. Features are then reduced with a Principal Component Analysis (PCA), where the model was fit to the training set and then transformed to the validation and test sets to avoid overfitting from information leaks.

The features remained after reduction were utilized to train multiple classifiers. The XGBoost model was optimized using RandomizedSearchCV, and assessed based on performance under three experimental conditions (i.e. using deep features only, fractal features only, and combined features). In addition to these baseline classifiers, advanced ensemble and attention-based classification strategies were implemented in stacking and attention-based architectures for the purposes of improving predictive performance.  

The last phase of the architecture incorporates explainable A.I. (XAI). Global explainability was achieved through their summary and feature importance showings, and local explainability by employing SHAP force or dependence plots that illustrated ways in which each prediction can be related to clinically interpretable features. 

Methods of visualization such as t-sne and umap were included to show both ease of separation and distribution and show decision boundaries used classify predictors with reduced sets. 

 

Overall, the system architecture is designed not just as a mechanism for obtaining peak predictive performance, but also to generate results that can be interpretable and informative for clinical applications.

## **3.3 Data Sources and Collection**

This research makes use of the CirCor DigiScope 2022 Phonocardiogram (PCG) dataset, which is a well-established and commonly used publicly-available benchmark set for heart sound classification and murmur detection tasks. The dataset contains over 3,163 recordings collected from pediatric patients in routine clinical visits at four hospitals in Brazil. Audio recordings use an electronic stethoscope in clinical settings, producing real-world variations in noise, background, and recording quality. The dataset includes audio samples sampled at 4000 Hz with length of 5-30 seconds. Heart sounds include normal and pathological murmurs, labelled by cardiologists. The dataset has multiple levels of annotations: murmur presence (present, absent, unknown), clinical outcome (normal, abnormal), and location of auscultation site (aortic, pulmonary, tricuspid, mitral). 

For this study, I adapted the dataset to a binary classification framework for normal heart sounds and abnormal/murmur-present recordings, similar to previous studies on PCG-based murmur detection. To address class imbalance, data augmentation techniques, including time-stretching, pitch-shifting, noise-injection, and amplitude-scaling, were applied afterwards in the preprocessing stage. The dataset was divided into training (70%), validation (15%), and test (15%) data, with stratification across classes to preserve the proportions of normal and abnormal samples. Patient-level splitting was enforced to avoid data leakage, ensuring that recordings from the same patient did not appear in the different datasets. This careful implementation improves the generalizability of the build model, consistent with accepted practices in utilizing machine learning in the biomedical research field.

## **3.4 Data Preprocessing**

Achieving success in accurately preprocessing phonocardiogram (PCG) signals is important to produce clean and representative input to downstream models. In this study, preprocessing was devised to tackle three main challenges of raw heart sound recordings: (i) variability in recording conditions, (ii) background and physiological noise and (iii) class imbalance from the lack of abnormal murmurs.

![][image11]

*Figure 3.2 Flowchart for PCG Preprocessing*

### **3.4.1 Normalization and Filtering**

First, the audio recordings underwent z-score normalization to standardize the distribution of amplitude across recordings. Then, a bandpass filter (20 \-500 Hz) was applied to the signal, which was parameter agnostic to the conditions of the PCG recordings and simply indicates the overlapping frequency span of heart sounds while also attenuating low frequency and high frequency background noise sources.

### **3.4.2 Segmentation**

After filtering, the filtered audio was segmented into 5s sections and overlapping segments of the overall recordings by 50%. This segmentation provided uniformity of input features length during training, while also increasing the potential size of the dataset without yielding independent duplicate samples. Segmentation based on patient recordings was maintained to reduce the potential for the introduction of leakage.

### **3.4.3 Data Augmentation**

In order to reduce the class imbalance and maximize class generalizability, the segmented signals were anatomically augmented with the following approaches (all approaches had parameters adjusted to represent realistic variability):

Time-stretching in between (± 10%) to mimic variations from subject’s heart rate

Pitch-shifting in between (±2 semitones) to account for differences from recording devices

Noise \- injected by maintaining 40 dB background noise to represent outer ambient mechanisms of interference

Amplitude \-scaled (±20%) to account for differences from applied pressure with stethoscope.

These approaches resulted in an overall increase of approximately three-fold on the dataset and balanced set for normal and abnormal samples to conduct downstream model training.

## **3.5 Feature Extraction**

Feature extraction is an important step in PCG-based machine learning, where raw/preprocessed audio signals are transformed into informative representations that highlight the physiological and pathological differences in heart sounds. In this paper, I use a dual-path feature extraction method, which includes deep features from convolutional neural networks (CNNs) on spectrogram representations as well as handcrafted fractal and entropy-based features that measure signal complexity. These complementary features were then fused together to create a comprehensive representation for classification.

![][image12]

*Figure 3.3 Flowchart for PCG Feature Extraction*

### **3.5.1 Deep Feature Extraction**

The first feature extraction outlined a method for learning discriminative spatial representations from time-frequency spectrograms of PCG recordings. Each segment of audio was transformed to a Mel-spectrogram with short-time Fourier transform (STFT) using 128 Mel bands and a hop length of 512\. The Mel scale was chosen due to its perceptual congruence with human hearing sensitivity, indicating that it best retains tonal structure of murmurs and other audio disturbances.

The spectrograms had their dynamic range normalized, and were resized to fixed size (128 × 128 pixels), which allowed convolutional networks models to expect standardized input. A pre-trained convolutional neural network (CNN), which utilized well-known architectures like ResNet-18 and VGG16, was used to extract features. Inference and transfer learning were possible by removing downstream classification layers and extracting embeddings from the next to last dense layer, which outputted a compact but high-dimensional feature vector \~ 512 dimensions per sample.

The embeddings preserved temporal-frequency signatures in PCG signals that represented frequency shifts, harmonic signatures, and time-based expressive behavior that were otherwise difficult to extract using traditional signal processing.

### **3.5.2 Fractal and Entropy: Feature Extraction**

The second feature extraction path used nonlinear dynamical measures to capture the complexity and irregularity of heart sounds. Where deep features represented spectral texture, fractal and entropy estimates measured the chaotic characteristics of PCG signals that typically predicted pathological murmurs.

The following estimates are calculated per 5-second window:

The Higuchi Fractal Dimension (HFD): the waveform complexity is quantified based on approximating fractal scaling.

Katz Fractal Dimension (KFD): Measures irregularity of the signal in relation to length and amplitude scaling.

Petrosian Fractal Dimension (PFD): Estimates the complexity based on sign changes in the derivative following the signal.

Detrended Fluctuation Analysis (DFA): extracts long-range temporal correlations in the heart sounds.

Hurst Exponent: Measures self-similarity and persistence of time-series.

Approximate Entropy (ApEn): quantifies unpredictability based on the signal.

Sample Entropy (SampEn): robust estimate of irregularity, less sensitive to length of data than ApEn.

Mean, standard deviation, max, min, and range were calculated for each signal.

### **3.5.3 Feature Fusion**

To leverage the complementary strengths of the two features sets, deep and fractal features were concatenated into a single vector representation. To avoid high-magnitude components from dominating the fusion, the two feature sets were scaled prior to fusion due to the variance in dimensionality (deep features: 512 dimensions, fractal features: 40-50 dimensions).

The fused feature set was subsequently processed for the next step, Principal Component Analysis (PCA), to capture redundancy and retain the most relevant axes of variation. This dual pathway fusion ensured that the model leverages both high-level spectral abstractions (deep CNN features) and low-level complexity measures (fractal/entropy features), improving predictive robustness.

## **3.6 Feature Scaling and Dimensionality Reduction**

The fused feature vectors generated from the deep embeddings and fractal/entropy measures were on different scales and dimensionalities. To achieve comparisons across features, and ultimately improve classifier performance, a two-phase procedure was followed: feature standardization followed by dimensionality reduction.

### **3.6.1 Feature Scaling**

The first step consisted of standardizing features via the method StandardScaler, which will rescale each feature dimension to have zero mean and unit variance. This was done to ensure that features with a large numerical range (i.e., fractal entropy values) would not dominate feature dimensions that had a small range (e.g., CNN activations). The feature scaling was performed separately for training, validation and test of the algorithm, but the scaler was fitted only once on the training set and applied to the other splits. This guarantees no data leakage, and maintains result evaluation integrity.

### **3.6.2 Principal Component Analysis (PCA)**

After scaling features were normalized, I applied Principal Component Analysis (PCA) to decrease feature dimensionality, while incorporating most of the variance in the fused feature space. PCA was fitted on embeddings from the training set only, and the transformation was then applied to the validation and test sets in separate operations.

This served two purposes:

* Mitigate redundancy: With highly correlated features that were derived from the CNN features, lots of redundancy was present among dimensions; PCA minimized dimensions into orthogonal principal component dimensions.  
* Better generalization: When dimensionally reduced features into a 80-100 dimension subspace (i.e., retained 95% variance), PCA also decreased the change of overfitting and computational burden from the classification algorithms.

  ### **3.6.3 Final Feature Sets**

At this point, three different standardized feature sets were produced for modeling: Deep-only features (i.e., PCA reduced CNN embeddings), Fractal-only features (i.e., PCA reduced handcrafted measures), and Fused features (i.e., concatenated deep \+ fractal features, which have been standardized and PCA reduced). These representations were the basis of machine learning models presented in the next section, classifiers were developed and tuned in parallel as benchmark predictive composite performance.

## **3.7 Model Training and Optimization**

The processed and scaled feature vectors which after scaling and dimensionality reduction, were used to train machine learning classifiers with an ensemble-based tree, Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost). This standard choice was driven primarily by the ability of models to accept moderate to high dimensional tabular data, offer some resistance to overfitting, and interpretationability across deep and fractal dimensions.

This modeling selection provided a consistent reference for comparisons of the discriminative potential of deep features, the discriminative potential of human-engineered fractal features, and using a combination of these features.

## **3.8 Advanced Fusion Techniques**

While the baseline models based on deep-only, fractal-only, and fused features were valuable benchmarks, more advanced, or advanced, fusion techniques were employed in order to use the complementary information provided in the feature sets and classifiers. By merging feature sets and ensembles of models, I hoped to obtain greater levels of generalizability and prediction accuracy. Two methods were utilized: stacking ensembles and attention-based fusion.

### **3.8.1 Stacking Ensemble**

Stacking, or stacked generalization, is a type of meta-learning, where a second-level model is trained based on the outputs of multiple base classifiers. In this case, the output of the fused features optimized XGBoost models was treated as input features in a logistic regression meta-classifier.

The meta-classifier learned when to place importance on base learner predictions, identifying how reliable they were to samples and rectifying systematic biases of each individual model. For example, XGBoost could capture the finely grained differences between elevated samples of automatic 11d and 11b features. Stacking reduced both variance and bias, it ensured that the predictions were more resilient than either base model.

### **3.8.2 Attention-Based Fusion Network**

An attention mechanism was also used to weight heavily, or lightly, the deep and fractal features during prediction. This is different than a concatenation in which your lump some features and thus consider them equally, the attention layer learned to assign global weights to the input features that highlighted a feature more than the other. The weights were adjusted so that the most informative features increased weights while problematically less relevant or noisy input dimensions attenuated them.

This method accomplished two things:

* Improved accuracy \- where the model could emphasize the most informative dimensions of the input, especially in contexts with overlapping features or highly correlated features.  
* Explainability \- the attention weights learned what the deep or fractal features emphasized more than the other features in each decision allowing us to explain the importance at the pathway level.

The attention module was incorporated as a neural layer following the concatenation of the deep and fractal features before the final classification layer to allow it to be incorporated in the pipeline.

### **3.8.3 Summary**

Together, stacking and attention-based fusion methods went beyond the baseline approaches through meta-learning and adaptive weighting. Stacking produced reliable predictions (by averaging classifier predictions), and the attention network gave features a level of interpretability and robustness beyond only layering on sampled features. These methods represent our advanced experimental setups, and explore whether adaptations to fusion presents quantifiable benefits in comparison to static feature concantenation.

## **3.9 Evaluation Strategy**

The evaluation strategy described here was intended to enable robust evaluation of model performance, consistency of experiment with respect to fairness, and straightforward interpretation of results. Models that were pre-trained on the deep-only, fractal-only, fused, and synthesized features were evaluated using a coordinated and diverse range of quantitative metrics, statistical tests and visualization.

### **3.9.1 Performance Metrics**

A wide and varied metric suite was employed to signify the performance metrics, which signify overall prediction accuracy, and clinical concerns are:

* Accuracy: The proportion of true instances classified correctly by the model and across classes.  
* Sensitivity (Recall): The portion of true positives (murmurs-present) classified correctly by a model. Clinical screening purposes should have very few false negatives  
* Specificity: The proportion of true negatives classified correctly by a model. This has reasons for unnecessary referrals.  
* Validity: The proportion of predicted positives that were ultimately true positives. This has ends to prevent unnecessary false positive cases.  
* F1 Measure: The harmonic mean of sensitivity and validity and provides a equitable overview of both types of error.  
* Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC-ROC): an approximation of the models ability to separate classes at multiple thresholds.

  ### **3.9.2 Cross-validation/Test protocol**

Model performance was first determined with the training set under 3-fold stratified cross-validation in order to maximize hyper-parameters, and evaluate generalization with respect to distributional properties over the validation data set. Stratification gave rise to balanced representation of normal and abnormal samples per fold.  
Final model (not over-fit) used to evaluate hold-out test data to have an estimated performance level Free from biases. Patient-level split was employed to ensure data did not leak from one to the other with each data set comprised of only one patient.

### **3.9.3 Confusion Matrix**

Here, confusion matrix per model helps explore errors of true positive, false negative, true negative and false positive, and enables model/comparison, or models/feature pathways comparisons.

### **3.9.4 Statistical Tests**

In order to find any statistically significant performance differences with pairwise comparison models, the McNemar test for paired prediction was used, together with competing models test set data. The McNemar Test a non-parametric paired test, used to test whether two classifiers differ significantly with respect to their Error distributions. This means any performance improvement is not random.

### **3.9.5 Visualize Results**

Visual means to also quantify results, potential of the ROC curves, for each model features set suggested an awareness regarding differences in both sensitivity and specificity at certain threshold for ultimate classification:

* Precision Recall Curve Analysis to also track performance under class imbalance real situation.  
* t-SNE and UMAP fused features plots for the subjective to view feature (normal and abnormal class) presence in reduced fiature space.

Thus, protocols therein illustrated meaningful performance consideration which converge predictive performance with clinical interpretability.

## **3.10 Explainability and Visualization**

In addition to predictive performance, the approach employed explainable artificial intelligence (XAI) techniques for interpreting the trained models. The aim was to enable transparent decision-making by allowing the clinician to visualize the global explainability trends in the features the models considered important, and to view the local explanations for the predictions. The two facets of interpretability allowed the PCG-based diagnostic system to provide the clinician with useful clinical recommendations in addition to accurate predictions.

![][image14]

*Figure 3.5 Flowchart for Explainability*

### **3.10.1 Global Explainability**

Global explainability techniques were used to summarize the main features that explained predictive power of the model over all data.

Rankings of deep and fractal features in order of magnitude on model predictions using SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) Summary Plots. SHAP values quantified the amount of each feature was positively influencing the decision on average. SHAP values are a more legitimate method of measuring the effect of each feature on the importance of the features for the model.

Gain importance for XGboost was integrated with, and compared with SHAP rankings to show either convergence or divergence of model driven (algorithmic) and game-theoretic explanations

Correlation Adult Analysis of certain redundancy or related features were analyzed regarding deep embeddings and fractal measures, to see specifically if they are representing additive and/or redundant formats.

### **3.10.2 Local Explainability**

Local explaining techniques were used to offer explanations for the predictions.

* SHAP Force Plots were used to visualize how features specifically influenced pushing the prediction value to “normal” and/or “abnormal.”  
* SHAP Dependence and Interactions Plots were visualized to show how pairs of features together co-influenced classification prediction from the model.  
* Clinical Interpretation: Mapping the decision trees of every model to physiological cues, whether it was through frequency spectrums of features, or the fractal measures demonstrated abnormal signal from either. These explainations provide a method of utilizing machine explanations within clinical decision-making.

  ### **3.10.3 Visualization**

For numerical explanations basis and SHAP-based methods, visualizations were also deployed:

* t-SNE and UMAP plots for exploring the multi-dimensional fused feature space in two-dimensions for visual ways evaluating separability class.  
* ROC and Precision–Recall Curves for summarizing performance of each of the models for visual overview of the trade-offs of sensitivity, specificity, and precision of the model.  
* The Attention Weights of the attention fusion network were exposed, for visualization in showing the relative weighting or attend matrices on deep and fractal feature importance.

  ### **3.10.4 Summary**

The usage of the global and local explainability method, with visualizations space and performance deliver to trustworthiness of the presented PCG-based diagnostic models, and explanations for clinical reasoning versus and accuracy. The effort of linking predictions to physiological reasoning bridges the gap to the utilization of AI-assisted auscultation evaluators in the healthcare setting.

## **3.11 Summary of Methodology**

The methodology outlined in this chapter involves the development of a phonocardiogram (PCG)-based system to predict valvular heart disease. The process consisted of eight phases: 1\) dataset collection, 2\) preprocessing, 3\) dual-path feature extraction, 4\) feature scaling and reduction, 5\) classifier training and optimization, 6\) advanced fusion strategies, 7\) evaluation, and 8\) explainability.

Starting with raw PCG recordings from the CirCor DigiScope dataset, I standardized the signals through normalization, bandpass filtering, segmentation, and augmentation to create a balanced dataset. Using two complementary feature extraction processes, I obtained deep embeddings from the Mel-spectrogram using a predefined CNN, and fractal/entropy features measuring the complexity of signals. The combinations of the 2 approaches were concatenated, standardized, and reduced in dimensionality via principal components analysis, resulting in informative features while minimizing redundancy.

Using the dimensional reduced features, XGBoost classifier was trained under 3 experimental scenarios (deep-only, fractal-only, and fused). Hyperparameters were optimized with RandomizedSearchCV and three-fold stratified cross-validation for model validation. To improve generalization beyond just using the fused features, advanced fusion methods (such as stacking ensembles and an attention-based fusion network) were employed. For evaluation, I used several metrics, including accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, precision, F1-score, and area-under-the-curve (AUC) of the receiver operating characteristic (ROC) curve, as well as confusion matrices, and McNemar’s test for over-fitting. For explainability, Iutilized global (e.g., SHAP summary, model importance) and local (e.g., force plots, dependence plots) methods, and used additional tools such as t-SNE/UMAP visualizers and ROC curves to display our results.

This 8-phase approach created a PCG-based system to predict valvular heart disease that was not only predictive, but clinically significant, and interpretable.

## **3.12 Computational Environment**

The implementation of the proposed methodology was carried out in Python 3.11 using both a local machine and a cloud environment.

Local Development Environment: For initial research and data preprocessing, and prototyping the pipeline visual studio Code (VS Code) was utilized on a local machine. The local development environment supported debugging, iterative development, and more flexibility.

Cloud Training Environment: Google Colab Pro was utilized for large experiments, and training of the model. Colab is fitted with high-performance GPUs that are more accessible, namely the NVIDIA Tesla T4 GPU available for some GPU computing that are computationally expensive (e.g., CNN based feature extraction) or hyperparameter optimization tasks. Compute credits were purchased to use the enhanced NVIDIA Tesla K80 GPU runtime sessions for Colab for more latency-free workloads, for all experiment runs at a lower cost than the free-tier.

Libraries and Frameworks: The experiments used a combination of the open-source Python libraries NumPy and Pandas (for handling data) Librosa (for signal processing) Scikit-learn (for machine learning and RandomizedSearchCV), XGBoost (for boosting classifiers), TensorFlow/Keras (for image feature sketch) and SHAP (for explainability).

With the dual-purpose set up of VS code for local development and colab pro for speed training, there were iterate reproducibility, as well as decrease in computation time. A Cloud-Based platforms allowed for a more reproducible/in a lack of better words’, iterative development process without taking disproportionate amount of time to do max compute on the task
